 England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Murphy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam, Aileen, Kieran, Brigid, Donal, Siobhan, Eamon, Aidan, Dermot, John Patrick, Declan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murchadha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Murchadh</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>muir</i> ‘sea’ + <i>cath</i> ‘battle’, i.e. ‘sea warrior’. This was an important family in Tyrone. For the surname with <i>mac</i>, see also   McMurrough   (Leinster).","English: variant of <b>Morphey</b> (see   Morphew  )."],"variants":[{"name":"McMurrough","meanings":["Irish:","Anglicized form (in Leinster) of <b>Mac Murchadha</b> ‘son of <i>Murchadh</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘sea warrior’. The spelling <i>gh</i> indicates the original guttural fricative sound of the internal <i>-ch-</i>. Elsewhere, in Roscommon and Tyrone, the usual Anglicized form was   Murphy   (the same phonetic change as in English <i>laugh, cough</i> etc.). Diarmait Mac Murchadha (Dermot McMurrough) was intermittently king of Leinster from 1126–71. After being deposed in 1166 he requested help from Henry II to reclaim his kingdom, which resulted in the Norman invasion of Ireland in 1169 under the leadership of Richard de Clare, Earl of Pembroke (known as ‘Strongbow’), an event that brought many Anglo-Norman surnames to Ireland. A powerful Irish family of this lineage were also known as   Kavanagh  , after Dermot's son.","Anglicized form (in Leinster) of <b>Mac Murchadha</b> ‘son of <i>Murchadh</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘sea warrior’. A powerful family of this name were also known as   Kavanagh  . The spelling <i>gh</i> indicates the original guttural fricative sound of the internal <i>-ch-</i>. Elsewhere (especially in Roscommon and Tyrone) the usual Anglicized form of the Irish name was   Murphy  ."]},{"name":"Morken","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Knut.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads so named, from the definite form of Old Norse <i>mǫrk</i> ‘outlying pasture, wood’.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murcháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Murchán</i>’, a diminutive of the personal name <i>Murchadh</i> (see   Murphy  )."]},{"name":"McMurphy","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Murchadha</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Murchadh</i> ‘sea warrior’, from <i>muir</i> ‘sea’ + <i>cath</i> ‘battle’. Compare   Murphy  ,   McMorrow  ,   McMurdo  ."]},{"name":"Murphrey","meanings":["Probably Irish: variant of   Murphy  ."]},{"name":"Morphis","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Murphy  ."]},{"name":"Morphy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Augusto, Jaime, Javier, Luis, Patricio.  Irish Donovan.","Scottish: variant of   Murphy  .","English (northern): variant of <b>Morphey</b> (see   Morphew  )."]},{"name":"Murphey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Murphy  .","English (mainly northern): variant of <b>Morphey</b> (see   Morphew  )."]},{"name":"Murphree","meanings":["Probably Irish: variant of   Murphy  ."]},{"name":"Morahan","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murcháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Murchán</i>’, a personal name, a pet form of <i>Murchadh</i> ‘sea-warrior’. See   Murphy  ."]}]},{"name":"Timothy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form, used in the Authorized Version of the Bible (alongside the Latin form <i>Timotheus</i>), of the Greek name <i>Timotheos</i>, from <i>timē</i> ‘honour’ + <i>theos</i> ‘god’. This was the name of a companion of  St Paul;  according to tradition, he was stoned to death for denouncing the worship of  Diana . It was not used in England before the Reformation but has been in steady use since the 18th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Timothy Murphy was born in 1460, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Mary O'Connor. He died in 1525, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1460–1525":"1460–1525","1460–1505":"1460–1505","1480–1556":"1480–1556","1525":"1525","1556":"1556","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1460–1525":"1460–1525","1460–1505":"1460–1505","1480–1556":"1480–1556","1525":"1525","1556":"1556","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1460–1525":"1460–1525","1460–1505":"1460–1505","1480–1556":"1480–1556","1525":"1525","1556":"1556","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Timothy Murphy est né en 1460, à Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Mary O'Connor. Il est décédé en 1525, à Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 65 ans."},"de":{"1460–1525":"1460–1525","1460–1505":"1460–1505","1480–1556":"1480–1556","1525":"1525","1556":"1556","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Timothy Murphy wurde 1460 in Somerset, England, United Kingdom geboren. Er hatte mit Mary O'Connor mindestens 1 Tochter. Er starb